The man accused of burning down the main house of Parliament, is said to have wandered around the precinct for at least 30 hours before he was nabbed. And, he’s believed to have used an accelerant to spur on the spread of the fire through two key buildings. The question is: how did Zandile Mafe allegedly dodge Parliament’s security systems for so long? Lindsay Dentlinger takes a look. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Zandile Mafe, the man accused of burning down the main house of Parliament, is said to have wandered around the precinct for at least 30 hours before he was nabbed. He’s believed to have used an accelerant to spur on the spread of the fire through two key buildings. These are some revelations from sources close to the investigation, who did not want to be named. WATCH | Zandile Mafe's lawyer speaks Sources say Mafe managed to dodge CCTV cameras which Parliament’s presiding officers have confirmed, were working, by crawling around. Security sources have confirmed the footage is now being closely guarded by the Hawks. More details related to Mafe’s alleged involvement in starting the fire, are expected to be revealed when he returns to court on Tuesday.